According to the report

“within the social context of fisher-farmers’ settlements in the region, social capital such as the community support and income, networks and accommodation (including health and welfare services) is fundamental to the livelihoods of fishing households and largely non-transferable (Fiedler, Welch-Devine & Wilkinson 1998, p. 6).

Moreover, higher functioning fishing communities tend to provide for their members with the availability of local government services and the infrastructure (Appendix IV). For instance, the Ilajes of Orerokpe community in Ughelli Local Government Area depend on their traditional ruler since he is the highest traditional authority in the community. Such institutions foster the fabrication of the social capital, but also make the availability of both private and community social capital dependent upon necessity.

Ocean Heat is the main driver for ocean acidification. When carbon dioxide is dissolved in the oceans, it essentially forms a weak acid. This acidic state changes how marine life, specifically mollusks and corals, do things like maintain their structures, exchange oxygen and carbon dioxide and build shells.
